{{Infobox military conflict |conflict=1977 Bogra mutiny |image= |caption= |date=30 September 1977 |place= |status=Defeat of the mutineers<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chakrabarti |first1=S. K. |year=1978 |title=The Evolution of Politics in Bangladesh, 1947-1978 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZHsBAAAAMAAJ&q=Bogra+mutiny+30+September+1977&dq=Bogra+mutiny+30+September+1977 |publisher=Associated |pages=251 |language=en}}</ref> |combatant1={{flagicon|Bangladesh}} [[Bangladesh Army]] |combatant2=Mutineers from the 22nd [[Bengal Regiment]] |commander1= |commander2= |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= |casualties3= |notes= }} The '''1977 Bogra mutiny''' was a [[mutiny]] in [[Bogra Cantonment]] on 30 September 1977.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rahman |first1=Syedur |year=2010 |title=Historical Dictionary of Bangladesh |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bJfcCPUr0OoC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=Bogra+mutiny+started+on+30+September+1977#v=onepage&q=Bogra%20mutiny%20started%20on%2030%20September%201977&f=false |publisher=Scarecrow Press |pages=55 |isbn=9780810874534 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sepoy Unrest in Bogra|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/1977DACCA05569_c.html|website=wikileaks.org |date=1 October 1977 |access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref>
==Background== [[Ziaur Rahman]] was the chief of Army Staff, he served as the chief Martial law administrator after the [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]. On 21 April 1977 President [[Abu Sadat Mohammad Sayem]] resigned and Zia became president of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ahamed|first1=Emajuddin|title=Rahman, Shahid Ziaur|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Rahman,_Shahid_Ziaur|website=en.banglapedia.org|publisher=Banglapedia|access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ziaur Rahman president of Bangladesh|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Ziaur-Rahman|website=britannica.com|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica|access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref> On July 1977 the Bogra cantonment saw another mutiny which led to the mutinous unit being disbanded. The cause behind the mutiny was resented over pay increase which were deemed insufficient.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sepoy Unrest in Bogra|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/1977DACCA05519_c.html|website=wikileaks.org |date=30 September 1977 |access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref>
==Events== The mutiny took place in Bogra cantonment under the leadership of Lieutenant Colonel Zaman. The government of Bangladesh was preoccupied with [[Japan Airlines Flight 472 (1977)|Japan Airlines Flight 472]] which was hijacked and had landed in Dhaka.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roy |first1=Asish Kumar |year=2002 |title=Praetorian politics in Bangladesh, 1975-1981 |publisher=Progressive Publishers |pages=78, 207 |oclc=491399557 |language=en}}</ref> Enlisted men had killed their officers and there were reports of gunfire in Bogra town.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bangladesh Mutiny|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/1977DACCA05677_c.html|website=wikileaks.org |date=4 October 1977 |access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref> The 22nd [[Bengal Regiment]] had mutinied. After the mutiny had failed, hundreds of soldiers were executed and buried in mass graves in [[Rajshahi District|Rajshahi]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Clandestine killings in the Bangladesh Army |url=http://www.observerbd.com/2014/01/19/1891.php |newspaper=Daily Observer |access-date=13 December 2016}}</ref> [[Syed Faruque Rahman]] one of the assassins of Sheikh Mujib was involved in the mutiny and his old unit was stationed in Bogra at that time.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ahmed |first1=Moudud |year=1995 |title=Democracy and the Challenge of Development: A Study of Politics and Military Interventions in Bangladesh |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ih2GAAAAMAAJ&q=Bogra+mutiny+30+September+1977&dq=Bogra+mutiny+30+September+1977 |publisher=Vikas Publishing House |pages=67 |isbn=9780706997262 |language=en}}</ref>
